Comparative analysis of monofacial and bifacial photovoltaic modules for floating power plants

Abstract

The aim of this study is to create usable commercial simulation software tools for photovoltaic (PV) systems even in the case of floating applications. Using the experimental data of a plant installed at the â€œEnel Innovation Labâ€ in Catania (IT), adequate heat exchange coefficients of the software's thermal models were found, which allowed us to take into account the thermal effects for these types of installations. An optimization of the sizes for mono- and bifacial floating systems was carried out. The simulated data for a ground system were compared with the floating data through performance indices. In addition, monofacial models were compared with bifacial. The optimized variables are the tilt angle and the pitch, whereas for the bifacial systems, the module elevation is also considered. The albedo is a sensitive factor mainly for the bifacial modules, so it was considered a parameter in the different design solutions. The simulations were performed by two specialized commercial software programs, where different PV system models are implemented. The normalized annual energy yield was chosen as a meaningful parameter with which to compare the different solutions. As the analysis of PV systems is highly site dependent, the study was developed for two locations, characterized by different diffuse and albedo solar irradiance components, specifically at high latitudes (Frankfurt, DE) and at intermediate latitudes (Catania, IT).

1. Introduction

One of the indicators used to measure the welfare of a country is electricity consumption because the majority of the energy produced every day by power plants is consumed by industry, and if it more energy, it means that there is more goods production and an increase in the countryâ€™s economy. With globalization and new market growth, in recent years, energy demand has increased. World electricity generation grew by 2.8% in 2017 [1], and production cannot rely exclusively on fossil fuel resources due to the pollution derived from their use. It is possible to use renewable sources, such as photovoltaics, but they have some problems, such as low power density.
To increase efficiency, systems with high-performance photovoltaic modules, such as bifacial modules, can be implemented and installed with methods that increase their efficiency, such as floating.
Bifacial PV modules can boost the performance of PV plants by 25â€“30% (and even more using reflecting solutions) depending on their electrical behaviour, mounting structures and terrain characteristics [2].
They are perceived as the technology that can be used for future solar power plants as they increase energy yield at a marginally higher cost. The efficiency of the bifacial modules depends on the temperature which therefore changes the energy yield and the LCOE by about 10â€“15% as demonstrated in [3].
The effect of bifaciality could also be exploited in the case of floating installations. In fact, multiple advantages of these installations have been reported in the literature. Some of these configurations are favourable for bifacial modules.
Floating photovoltaic projects are growing in both number and scale. Since 2015, more than 100 plants have begun operation worldwide as top hydropower reservoirs, industrial water sites, aquaculture ponds and other water bodies [4]. The benefits of putting solar modules into main water bodies include increased economic output per unit of land, improved output (likely due to the cooling effect of water on solar panels) and reduced water evaporation. Japan leads in the number of floating plants, due in part to the countryâ€™s FIT policy combined with the limited roof and ground space for solar PV systems [5]. Other countries with projects include China, with approximately 400 MW of floating capacity, India, the Republic of Korea and Brazil; Brazilâ€™s first floating project was completed in 2017 [6]. In addition to classic applications on lakes and reservoirs, floating systems can also be installed offshore, as suggested in [7], or integrated with hydroelectric plants [8]. A solution that exploits the synergy between water-food-energy (WFE) has been proposed in the literature, and consists in implementing a floating photovoltaic-hydroelectric hybrid system in which there is the possibility of creating fish farms [9].
Other applications similar to FPVs, which have their own benefits, are â€œCanal top solar systemsâ€, installed on rivers and water channels in which there are favourable microclimate conditions that help increase efficiency and reduce the degradation rate of modules [10].
The performance prediction of a photovoltaic system is very important both in the design phase to facilitate its realization and assess its feasibility and in the operational phase to solve any problems due to the malfunction of the system components [11]. For PV performance prediction, there are a lot of simulation software that basically categorized in, economic evaluation tools, analysis and planning tools, monitoring and control tools, solar radiation maps and some other online software [12]. The most popular software programs in recent years are PVSYST, HOMER, SAM (System Advisor Model), PVSOL, TRNSYS, Solar Pro and many others mentioned in [13].
Given the considerable number of software tools that basically have the same purpose but calculate the variables involved in a photovoltaic system in different ways, it is necessary to understand how they are calculated, the differences that exist between them and the error made against measured data. The variables on which the power produced depends are manifold but are mainly meteorological variables and the temperature of the photovoltaic modules. For the latter, to obtain reliable results from the models, we must take into account the technology (mono-polycrystalline, amorphous heterojunction etc.), the characteristics of the module (monofacial, bifacial, glass-glass or glass-backsheet) [14], the type of installation (free with air circulation, semi integrated, with insulated rear part, on roofs, on water, etc.) [15]. In fact, at the STC reference temperature (25 Â°C), crystalline PV technologies have typical power temperature coefficients of between 0.003 Â°Câˆ’1 and 0.005 Â°Câˆ’1 for monocrystalline, 0.004 Â°Câˆ’1 for polycrystalline and between 0.0011 Â°Câˆ’1 and 0.0026 Â°Câˆ’1 for amorphous PV technologies [16].
Many models for PV modelling, and, therefore, the power produced by it, have been proposed over the years [17], but in this case, it is necessary to use the most suitable model in relation to the technology and characteristics of the PV modules [18].
From a careful bibliographic analysis, it has been noted that there is a gap regarding the existence of commercial software suitable for modelling floating photovoltaic systems. The arguments for which the treatment of floating systems can be different from normal systems, in principle, are the following:
- The temperature of the modules. Due to evaporation and the local microclimate, the ambient temperature near the modules may be slightly lower than the temperature measured in the soil area. Therefore, to take into account the natural cooling of the modules, it is necessary to adequately choose the heat exchange coefficients of the temperature models used by the software.
- The albedo. The albedo of a water body is very low (0.1, which is much lower than the normal value of 0.2 for soil). For large monofacial installations, the albedo is not significant, as it is only â€œseenâ€ from the first row of modules. For bifacial systems, this property is not true since the back of modules also captures solar radiation.
Therefore, the objective of this work is to make two commercial software tools accessible through appropriate adjustments in the models for applications in water.
For this reason, it was necessary to compare the models with experimental data to obtain the correct value of the heat transfer coefficient for a thermal model used in the software in the case of floating systems.
Moreover, the purpose of this study is to find the optimal geometric configuration for a floating photovoltaic system in relation to the geometric variables, albedo values and installation location.
In this work, we compare, both in terms of power and temperature of the modules, two commercial software programs used for the study of photovoltaic systems to verify the reliability of the data obtained, even in the case of applications of floating photovoltaic systems. For this goal, a system installed on an artificial basin was monitored at the Enel Innovation Lab in Catania (Italy), which allowed us to compare the experimental data with the model results.
The novelty of this study is the use of commercial software for floating applications, particularly to simulate the optimization of the energy collected (optimal geometrical design) in relation to the geometric configuration, as well as the evaluation of the performance of the bifacial modules. The comparison in terms of the power and temperature of a cell between the software models and the experimental data of a floating system is also a novelty. To obtain the temperature data of the models compatible with those of a floating system, which enjoys natural cooling due to the favourable microclimate conditions, the thermal models were calibrated, and appropriate values of the heat exchange coefficients were chosen. In doing so, commercial software was made available, even for floating systems.
This paper is organized as described below:
-In Section 2, the characteristics of the studied system are illustrated, it corresponds to the one installed in EGP laboratories from which the experimental data and the geometric parameters have been obtained;
-In Section 3, the experimental data obtained from the floating photovoltaic system installed in Catania, IT, with the data obtained from the models from the two software packages csw1 and csw2 are compared. Therefore, the models of the two csw programs in the case of mono- and bifacial systems with the experimental data in terms of both the power and temperature of the modules are compared. The objective is to find the heat transfer coefficients of the temperature models of the mono and bifacial modules, suitable for installations of floating systems, through a MATLAB optimization algorithm that minimizes the RMSE between the measured and calculated data.
In the second part of the section are compared models for mono and bifacial modules used by the two software csw1 and csw2 for two different locations (Catania IT, Frankfurt D) to make a critical analysis of the results. Moreover, the optimal geometric configuration in relation to the energy produced and compared with the systems on the ground in terms of energy yield compared to the floating systems is calculated.

2. Sites and photovoltaic systems data

The PV floating system analysed consists of two floating PV fields, one made of monofacial modules and the other made of bifacial modules. The PV systems studied in this paper are realized at the experimental site of the Enel Innovation Lab (Enel Green Power) in Catania (Italy).
The system simulations are developed by two software tools, hereinafter referred to as csw1 and csw2, while data processing was performed in the MATLAB environment.

2.1. Characteristics of the system components

Each field, whose rated power is 3.84 kW for the monofacial modules and 4.14 kW for the bifacial modules, has 12 modules, divided into 2 strings that are connected to a multi-string inverter equipped with separate MPP trackers. The configuration and connection of the strings is shown in Fig. 1, where they are highlighted with different colours (light blue and dark blue for the monofacial modules and light grey and dark grey for the bifacial modules). The characteristics of the PV modules are shown in Table 1, and those of the inverter are shown in Table 2.

The waves and wind effects on the water surface substantially change the surface structure, raising its reflectivity [19]; in this regard, simulations were performed at different albedo values. During the simulations, the albedo was assumed to be a constant, since in most cases, these systems are installed at sites where the presence of waves is limited. It is clear that when there is a noticeable rippling of the surface of the water, the phenomenon of the diffusion of the reflected radiation is generated; therefore, considering a constant albedo is no longer possible.
These two sites were chosen to evaluate the behaviour of the bifacial modules at different latitudes, where the percentage of diffuse horizontal irradiance (DHI) with respect to the global horizontal irradiance (GHI) is different. In this regard, the diffuse irradiance factor fd can be defined as follows:(1)fd=DHIGHI
Higher values of fdwould cause an increase in bifacial module production since it would receive more rear-side irradiation [20]. Specifically, fd is equal to 0.329 in Catania and 0.511 in Frankfurt.

2.3. Geometric variables

The simulations were carried out by changing the three geometrical parameters of the PV systems, graphically described in Fig. 2. Specifically, the pitch, dr, is normalized with respect to the length of the module, L (the dimension of the PV module perpendicular to the row direction); for bifacial systems, the height from the surface of the water, hw, is also considered. The optimization variables assume discrete values. Table 4 reports the lower and upper bounds of the variables and the number of steps.

Table 4. Geometrical variables of the PV systems.

VariableMin. valueMax. valueDiscrete value number
Î³Mm/b (Â°)5306
dr/L1.252.06
hw (m)01.56
Both in the design phase and in the estimation of the performance of a floating system, it is appropriate to take into account the impact of wind and waves stresses on the floating structure. Whose intensity depends on the local environmental conditions as well as the characteristics of the basin [21].
The energy performances could change if the geometric variables, such as tilt and the azimuth angles, change during the passage of the waves under the floating structure.
As for azimuth angle, thanks to the use of effective mooring solutions, for instance by elastic mooring systems [21] the effect on production in relation to the change of orientation of a few degrees is negligible.
The effect on tilt of the passage of a wave is reported in Fig. 3, at the beginning the pontoon is in a horizontal condition and the angle of incidence between the normal to the module and the solar beam is Î¸0, subsequently, at the wave passage, the pontoon tilts and the angle of incidence becomes Î¸0 + Î¸waves, in the next phase it tilts an angle opposite to the previous one and the angle of incidence is Î¸0-Î¸waves and finally in the last phase it returns to the state of quiet with angle of incidence Î¸0.
Under the assumption that the PV system is working at maximum power point, as a first approximation, the PV power is, proportional to the irradiance, so there is linear dependency between Power and G.
Under this assumption the global effect of the variation of the tilt angle on the energy production is nil.
On the other hand, the impact of the variation of the temperature due to the variation of G can be neglected due to the thermal inertia of the PV module and the frequency of the wave phenomenon.
The impact of tilt variation is also dependent on the type of floating structure [22], since in case of rigid floating platforms the waves affect the orientation of the whole PV system, whereas in case of no rigid floating systems some PV modules can undergo to a local angle variation. In this case a mismatch of irradiance among modules that belong to the same string can determine losses [23].
In the final analysis it is important to emphasize that usually floating photovoltaics are designed for water basins where there are favourable climatic conditions (low wind and waves). Whereas for offshore applications, both from the point of view of the high demanding mechanical design of the structures and of duration of the components (reduced due to the salty ambient), it may not be convenient [24]. Moreover, in the latter case, appropriate simulation models may be needed for performance evaluation [25].

2.4. Comparison indices

A performance comparison between mono- and bifacial systems is critical due to both different definitions of rated power and converted solar energy quantities.
In this paper, first, the yearly energy yield Yâ€™, in kWh, is evaluated (it is the sum of hourly average power values under the hypothesis that the system works at maximum power point, MPP, see (2) and (2â€²)), then it is normalized with respect to peak power, in kW. The subscripts m and b indicate the monofacial system and the bifacial system, respectively:(2)Ym=âˆ‘t=0nPmpp,m(t)Î”tPmpp,m=Y'mPmpp,m(2â€²)Yb=âˆ‘t=0nPmpp,b(t)Î”tPmpp,b=Y'bPmpp,b
It is worth noting that Yâ€™b is normalized with respect to the front-side module power Pmpp,b.
The bifacial gain, BF (in %), is defined as:(3)BF=100Yb-YmYm
The BF is used to evaluate the energy gain of a bifacial system compared to a monofacial system.
The comparison of the performance between the ground and floating systems is important for evaluating the actual increase in energy produced. To evaluate this increase, we calculated the floating gain (FG).
The floating gain FG, in %, is defined as:(4)FG=100Yfl-YgrYgr
The FG is used to compare the producibility of a floating system compared to a ground system. The ground system is taken as a reference, in which the heat exchange coefficients of the thermal models are those usually used for free mounted systems with air circulation and are compared with the floating systems whose heat exchange coefficients of the thermal models are those obtained for the floating experimental plant installed at the â€œEnel Innovation Labâ€ of Enel Green Power in Catania (IT) at section â€œCalibration of modelsâ€.

3. Optimization and models comparison

In this section, the models of the mono and bifacial systems will be compared, and an optimization of the producibility with respect to the geometric variables of the photovoltaic system will be carried out.
The used software programs for simulations are respectively: PVsyst (csw1), which is a commercial software specialized for sizing and analysis of PV systems and SAM (csw2) which is a free techno-economic software that facilitates decision-making for people in the renewable energy industry.
The two programs have been chosen as they are more common on the market and to give the possibility of use to users of paid or free licenses. Furthermore, among the software tools on the market, used for calculating the performance of the PV systems, these give the possibility of simulating also bifacial PV systems.
To verify the reliability of both software also in the case of bifacial systems, a comparison between the models used by the two software was made and the results are reported in Section 3.2.

3.1. Calibration of models

To adapt the software models to the floating applications, the experimental data were compared with the models of the two software programs, csw1 and csw2, where the following geometric configuration was considered: dr/L = 1.55, Î³Mm/b = 20Â° and hw = 0.4 m. The heat exchange coefficients of the models, which minimized the error with respect to the measured data, both in terms of temperature and estimated power, were obtained.
The characteristics of the system shown in Fig. 4 are described in 'SITES AND PV SYSTEMS DATA'. The PV module temperature, current, voltage and DC and AC power produced by the two systems were measured as well as the environmental variables. Specifically, ambient temperature, diffuse and global solar irradiance, and wind speed are the inputs of the software used to simulate the systems. These data were collected by the meteorological station (Fig. 5) run by Enel Green Power. It is positioned (37Â° 24â€²41.4 â€œN 15Â° 02â€²38.4â€³ E, IT) near the perimeter of the reservoir where the floating photovoltaic system is installed. In order to make the software usable in the case of floating systems, an optimization algorithm has been developed whose purpose is to obtain the heat transfer coefficients of Eqs. For the optimization of the coefficients, the MATLAB function 'fmincon' was used, the operative variables (U0, U1, a and b) are forced to vary between lower and upper limits to maintain their physical values and, the optimization function was the minimization of the RMSE (Eq.5) between the measurements and the numerical results.

3.1.3. Power comparison

In this paragraph, the power measured in the experimental systems of both mono- and bifacial modules are compared with the power calculated by csw1 and csw2. From the analysis of the electrical behaviour of the two strings of each system, it has been noted that they show the same behaviour in terms of power production, so for the sake of simplicity, the power of a single string for each system is reported. The comparison power was the upstream of the inverter (DC). The models used by the csw1 software for calculating the power are described in [27], while for the csw2 software are described in [28].
3.1.3.1. Monofacial PV plant results:
Fig. 10 shows the plot of the measured power on a string of the monofacial system (solid line) and the plots of the power calculated by csw1 and csw2 (dashed lines). It is worth noticing that during clear days the software csw2 underestimates the power. On cloudy days both software are very close to the measured values.
3.1.3.2. Bifacial PV plant results:
Fig. 11 shows the plot of the measured power on a string of the bifacial system (solid line) and the plots of the power calculated by csw1 and csw2 (dashed lines). It is worth noting that during clear days, csw1 overestimates the power. On cloudy days, the calculated values of both software programs are very close to the measured values.

3.2. Software comparison

The purpose of this paragraph is to compare the quantities obtained by the two software in order to calculate the differences in the results, and evaluate the possibility to continue with the study, through the use of a single software. Fig. 12 shows a logic diagram that accompany the two software.
To this aim a comparison about modeling bifacial systems between the software csw1 (indicated by 1) and csw2 (indicated by 2), is performed. In this case only one-row PV array layout is considered. The simulations were carried out at hw = 0 m and a = 20%.
The objective of this analysis is also to understand to which parameter attribute any differences.
As it is possible to notice in Table 8 and Table 9, due to the inclination of the module Î³M equal to zero, both software lead to similar results, with a difference of EArrNom of 3.9% and 2.6% for Catania and Frankfurt respectively. This shows that the use of one rather than the other software in the case of monofacial systems (zero inclination, therefore the effect of the rear part is zero) is indifferent for the purpose of estimating the energy performance of a PV system, in that Î” value are less than 5%.

The calculated final energy results can be attributed to the different calculation methods, module losses and incident solar energy on the front and back of PV modules [29]. Regarding the thermal losses, the thermal models of PV modules used in the two software tools are different; in fact, csw2 uses a module loss calculation metric that is the heat transfer method [28], while csw1 uses another heat transfer method [27].

3.3. Monofacial vs bifacial models comparison and optimization

In this section, the optimal geometrical design of PV systems is performed by the csw1 software. The objective of the problem is the maximization of the yearly normalized energy, Y, whereas the operative variables are the geometrical variables reported in Table 4. The albedo is considered a parameter.
The model of the PV system is bi-dimensional, and it has been assumed that the shed layout is made of 40 rows. The electrical losses due to near shading are taken into account in the evaluation of Y, considering 3 bypass diodes in each PV module.
For the bifacial model, mismatch losses on the back of the module equal 2.5% and losses due to the shading of the structures equal 2.5% were considered. Furthermore, a 10% shed transparent fraction was considered.
For each location, indices were calculated with which the bifacial modules are compared with the monofacial modules and, again, the floating systems with those on the ground. The values of Ym/b-gr are calculated using the heat exchange coefficients of the thermal models for installations of free mounted modules with air circulation, while the values of Ym/b-fl are calculated using the coefficients obtained starting from the experimental data of the plant installed at the â€œEnel Innovation Labâ€ in Catania (IT).
The data acquisition and processing algorithm used for the geometric optimization of the system in the two case studies examined is shown in the Fig. 13.

The BF with hw = 0.9 m for ground systems reaches up to 11.0%, while it reaches up to 13.5% for floating systems. The results highlight the fact that in the presence of more diffuse radiation, bifacial systems increase their energy yield.

4. Conclusion

In the present study, heat transfer coefficients of the thermal models from commercial software for the simulation of photovoltaic systems suitable for the installation of floating systems were obtained. This suitability made it possible to create two commercial software packages accessible for applications on water bodies and to compare the systems on the ground with those on the water from an energy point of view. In the second analysis, the optimal configuration of a ground and floating system with mono- and bifacial modules, taking into account the most important geometrical parameters (tilt, pitch, and height from the water) and albedo, was developed. It was shown that with the studied configurations, it is possible to obtain energy gains with bifacial modules, which reach up to 13.5% compared to monofacial configurations. Furthermore, for the two studied sites (Catania and Frankfurt), it was noted that in Frankfurt, where the diffusion factor is greater than in Catania, there is a greater bifacial gain. Monofacial systems, unlike bifacial systems, have a lower sensitivity to albedo.
The increase in energy Î”Y in the bifacial system is greater than that in the monofacial system with the same pitch. At the same pitch, the bifacial system to be optimized, requires a higher tilt than the monofacial system.
For the analysed configurations, the trend of the BF as a function of hw is exponential and then levels off at 0.9 m, as shown in Figs. 15 and 17.
Furthermore, if the pitch is increased up to 2.5 m, the saturation point of hw will move to 1.5 m, and a BF up to 15% can be obtained with such configurations.
Using the heat transfer coefficients for thermal models obtained from the experimental data of the floating plant installed in Catania, we obtained a gain of floating systems (FG) between 3.4 and 5.8% for Frankfurt and between 4.5 and 7.3% for Catania.
In the case of floating systems, to take into account the natural cooling of the modules due to the favourable microclimate and to obtain more precise results, one needs to use software that allows the tuning of the thermal models in order to consider the cooling of the modules.

  • Floating photovoltaics could mitigate climate change impacts on water body temperature and stratification

    2021, Solar Energy
    Citation Excerpt :

    FPV systems are typically comprised of five main components: a pontoon of floaters, a mooring system, PV modules, cabling, and connectors (Sahu et al., 2016). The specific design of a system can be adapted to suit water body function and application through variations to floater material (Oliveira-Pinto and Stokkermans, 2020), PV module type (Tina et al., 2021; Ziar et al., 2020), orientation (Campana et al., 2019), and surface coverage (Cagle et al., 2020). However, each combination of components will have a unique impact on the atmospheric drivers of lake dynamics, potentially resulting in a large variation in lake function impacts between systems.
